<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="98" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="98" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sukhor" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="Paramollugo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paramollugo simulans" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Paramollugo simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thulin" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Lam." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="Paramollugo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paramollugo nudicaulis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nudicaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Paramollugo nudicaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs by having colliculate seed surface (testa cells slightly convex, not papillae-like) with no striate secondary cell ornamentation. Some forms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sukhor" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="Paramollugo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paramollugo simulans" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="simulans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Paramollugo simulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with linear leaves look like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thulin" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="M. G. Gilbert &amp; M. Thulin" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="Paramollugo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paramollugo angustifolia" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Paramollugo angustifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they reliably differ by the seed size (0.55-0.7 mm and 0.35-0.45 mm, respectively).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
Annual to 25(30) cm; leaves (5-9)10-25, rosulate, rather thin, obovate, narrowly oblong, sometimes lanceolate, 20-50 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-12 mm, continuously tapered in petiole (up to 20 mm) or rarely not clearly divided into petiole and blade if lanceolate or linear, glabrous or shortly papillate; stems many (rarely 1 in underdeveloped 
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="99" start="start">exemplars</pageBreakToken>
), branched in the middle part with many lateral branches forming loose inflorescence with semi-spherical habit, always with short (up to 20 mm) sterile branches (not carrying flowers); peduncles to 15 mm, basally with white or brownish bract to 1.5 mm; flowers 3-4 mm in diameter when open; perianth segments 1.3-1.7 mm long in flowering, 2-2.4 mm long in fruiting, ovoid, green from abaxial side, white or pinkish inside; stamens 5 to 10, anthers elliptic, 0.30-0.35 mm; capsule 3-valved, ovoid, 1.5-2.3 mm, contains (8)10-18 seeds; seeds are reniform, dark red or almost black, 0.55-0.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3 mm, with colliculate ultrasculpture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="99" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="99">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="99">Sandy, rocky, ruderal sites or dry forests at elevations 0-1700 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="99" type="flowering and fruiting">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="99">Flowering and fruiting.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="99">November-June.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
